  &lt;a data-fancybox=&#34;&#34; href=&#34;https://arturgower.github.io/img/multiple-waves-diagram.png&#34; data-caption=&#34;Caption: When an incident plane wave $\mathrm e^{i \mathbf k \cdot (x,y)}$ with $\mathbf k = k(\cos \theta, \sin \theta)$, encounters an (ensemble-averaged) particulate material, it excites many transmitted plane waves and one reflected plane wave. The transmitted waves are of the form $\mathrm e^{i \mathbf s_p \cdot (x,y)}$ with wavenumbers $\mathbf s_p = S_p (\cos \theta_p, \sin \theta_p)$ (details in paper) where both $S_p$ and $\theta_p$ are complex numbers. The larger Im $\mathbf s_p$, the more quickly the wave attenuates as it propagates into the half-space and the smaller the drawn vector for that wave above.&#34;&gt;
